text: You had me until "save the world". That's not what Tomb Raider's about. What Lara does means something to her personally, that's what drives the games, and since people not only play as her but come to care about her as a character, then what's important to her becomes important to the audience. The whole "save the world" thing has become far too overplayed and impersonal. Look at Civil War for example. The world wasn't at stake, everything that was at stake was personal to the characters and people cared about them so much, that their personal struggles came to mean something to audiences, people connected with the characters. This feels generic and impersonal right from the get go. If I wanted this and wanted to feel some personal gravity about the situation, I'd play the reboot game. You tried, but not hard enough.  Also, when you make the stakes "Save the world" you put yourself into a situation where there's only one possible outcome, so you already know how this ends. Spoiler alert: She saves the world, sequel teaser, end.

text: I was looking forward to this and I loved the 2013 reboot, but all this Trailer gets from me is a shrug and a meh. To me, this lacks soul. I don't get the adventure vibe, I don't get the feeling that she is in danger, afraid, emotional, vulnerable, alive.   It looks not as fun as the Indy movies, the National Treasure movies, the Fraser Mummy movies, and not even as the Jolie Lara Croft movies, as they all left me with intrigue and excitement, even the trailers. It's also not as cool as the Fast movies or as witty as the Kingsmen. It looks almost more like another boring Far Cry movie, even though it hits so much TR beats.  This has such a generic by the numbers feel to it and looks like a 6-7/10 netflix adaptation where I tell my friends that I was surprised the effects looked not as cheap as expected, but only watch it because it's part of the subscription and when you got nothing else to do.   The music and voiceover doesn't help either, it has a fanmade trailer vibe to it.   Only Nick Frosts appearance made me go "ooooh" and I smiled. It is the only positive reaction I had watching this trailer. Not the pun, just him being there. When this is the best part of the trailer, I feel worried for the movie.

text: Dear movie studios, could you please finally manufacture an original script and just insert the "game's skin" on top of it? I'd like to use Logan here as an example. At its heart, it was a great drama film with some X and adamantium sprinkled in the mix. It wasn't your basic superhero movie with CGI etc. Someone should take similar action with video game movies and break the cycle. I know creating something new might seem difficult and daunting as we saw with Assassin's Creed. But they lost their way with the 85% modern day stuff. Find the aspect which makes the game amazing and build on that. Just don't rehash the story from the game because most of us have already spent tens of hours experiencing it.  TL;DR Pls break teh cycle and git gud.

text: Feels too similar to the game, I know that's what they're going for but it's a little too similar, well not a little really but much. I mean why would I watch that movie if I already played the game? or watch it over playing the game? usually movies based on video games offer a lesser experience than playing the actual game, that doesn't always have to be the case but unfortunately it's the truth, and since the video game and the movie both seem to offer the exact same thing with very very tiny variations between the two it seems, and if I have access to a computer and can actually play the game why would I go for the lesser experience? I'm not bashing the movie but for me movie adaptation of the game shouldn't be near carbon copy of the game, it should offer me something interesting or relatively new, while of course staying true to the source material, the way they went about this movie just feels lazy to me.

text: "Give it a chance" NOPE FUCK THAT SHIT. Fool me once shame on you, fool me twice shame on me, fool me three times and you're officially *that* guy. Yeah this shit looks worse than Assassin's Creed which also had a great big star actor who had no right to be in a video game "adaption". That CGI is god awful too, this is considered decent enough to show to the public for a multimillion dollar movie? For fucks sake they couldn't even get a poster right by making the environment and clothing look fake as well as her tool but looked like she elongated her neck. Plus she looks nothing close to either the original or the reboot. You can not say that she has the lack of a figure and still say she looks like either of the two sources. And I'm sensing a complete tonal shift near the end of the trailer. That's the ending scene. 100%. It's a bullshit cliffhanger "look at her lookin all badass ready to go on another wacky adventure. Look she even has her guns, wow wee". Does it want to be the reboot or does it want to be like the original. Because if they keep trying to do both the movie is just going to be an incoherent mess with an identity problem. Plus it looks like every other video game movie. It looks nearly identical to the likes of Prince of Persia and Assassin's Creed.

text: Ok I know how it will sound but hear me out: This version looks a lot like a Mary Sue. Let me explain.  A Mary Sue character most important feature is that everything in the world revolves around her (or him, if it is a Gary Stu, aka male). Everything about the story and the plot is build around the character. She is good at everything she does and everybody is admiring her even if there is no noticable reason for it. Just her name is causing a reaction although she never did anything to earn that reaction. Never breaking a sweat despite doing things an actual athlete might fail and she beeing a skinny teenager. And she is doing all that while looking pretty.  Even if all of that wouldn't be true the trailer is still very generic, showing mostly the highlights of the action scenes (which are most likely 90% of all the good action scenes in the movie. Because trailers..) and bulletpoints of the story. if there is any good action in the movie you don't see it in this trailer. Most of the acting here is staring in the distance like so many other young female actresses in the last years..  TL;DR: not impressed. It looks a lot like any other lazy franchise adaptation of the last decades. If it isn't the trailer didn't show that. I expect a run to the mill action movie that will do good enough at the box-office but not that many liked all that much.

text: It's unbelievable how nitpicky and spoiled people are. It's actually rather hilarious. Big whoop it has a couple of corny lines, that doesn't make the movie. I mean, if it does for you, I feel really bad for you if one little flaw can make or break an entire piece of entertainment. Idk, audiences these days seemed to have very restricted and narrow minds, very little room for anything else besides ridiculously high standards, or just a very very specific thing they want, that if they don't get it's terrible right off the bat. Haters act like a bunch of children in a candy shop, but they don't get the exact candy they want. There's a variation of it, in the same flavor, but since it's not the EXACT candy they want, it's terrible... even without trying it. They just look at it and go, "Well, it's not the candy I want, so it's terrible. WAAAAHHH!! I WANT MY CANDY!!!!! *draws a shitty picture* THIS ONE!!!! GIVE IT TO ME NOW!!!! *stomps feet*" <--- That's what all the haters in this comment section sound like. I mean, really... if you actually listen to yourselves rofl. It's rather amusing. Anyway, you guys can enjoy NOT enjoying anything in your lives due to Nitpick Syndrome, meanwhile I'm going to enjoy life and the epic-looking movies that come out throughout, such as this one (and no, I don't think it's perfect, but nothing is perfect and nothing has to be perfect to be enjoyable, I know that's a very new concept for most of you, but that's the truth).

text: It looks like it'll make the mistakes that Assassin Creed did.  Every video game to movie translation is the same: "We need huge action sequences!  The bigger, the better!  Character development? Protagonist charisma? Pfft!  Who has time for that!!!!"  These writers and directors hear 'video game origin' and instantly forget the reason people like/love certain characters is because of their personalities and charm, ie: Nathan Drake, Lara Croft, etc.; it's not JUST about the jumping and shooting that draws in the fan base.  Game adaptations always seem to ignore that little fact and only focus on the action and explosions... thus they're always doomed to mediocrity.  They just 'insert XYZ' actor who is hot atm and figure that will entice people into the theater.  I guess we'll have to wait and see, but the "I have to SAVE THE WORLD!" trope doesn't give me much hope.

text: It's too stuck in the middle of the old and new Lara Croft. And she doesn't really look like the new Lara Croft. She doesn't look British enough. She looks more American. She doesn't have that English face. Also too skinny. Not as big a deal as with Wonder Woman, but still off. I mean, when you're so skinny you're skinnier than the rebooted Lara, you gotta put on some skin. Old Lara=thicc hot toned lady. New Lara=normal body, toned and pretty. This Lara=skinny almost lanky body, toned, and okay looking. I just think the casting was off. Hopefully, the acting is good. I mean, the suspension of disbelief is already there but it's fine because it's a video game and it's Lara Croft, but when you make her even skinnier than the reboot, and seemingly less muscle mass, how am I to believe she won't just die when she falls from a ledge? And based on what little footage we've seen, she doesn't really seem to act like the new or old Lara. Maybe it'll turn out fine, but she just seems kinda bland. This trailer just gives me bad Assassin's Creed movie vibes.

text: I'm really disappointed with the negative reactions here, Lara Croft is an idol of mine and will forever be one of my favorite video game franchises and character. I personally don't care about her physical traits, as long as they at least get the accent, hair, and eye color right. Which they did. Boobs should be entirely irrelevant. Lara was much more than that, she was intelligent, fierce, brave, and a complete badass who was willing to stop whoever or whatever was in the way of her objective. My only complaint with Tomb Raider was the rebooted game itself because it took a lot away from why we all loved playing as Lara. The classic Lara will forever be my favorite. At least for me, and she was iconic with her dual pistols- which made me so sad to see them stripped away in the reboot. So the last scene here had such an impact because the director here saw an opportunity to bridge a gap between the original we know and love with the reboot, which wasn't bad but could have been better. This is just an opinion, and everyone is entitled to their own of course, I am just choosing to be optimistic about this as a fan. So fingers crossed that this film breaks the curse of video game based films.    P.S   Did anyone else feel overjoyed when they saw the iconic pistols????

text: This seem to lack the same thing the new Tomb Raider games lack. And that is charm. The new Tomb Raider games are fine and I did really enjoy the first one, but I found the second one to be kinda tedious. And the story is fairly boring to me. For a treasure hunter story it really lacks something the charm that the great ones have. Such as Indiana Jones and the old Mummy films. And especially from the leading character. The new Lara is just way too serious for my tastes and she seems to be the same in this movie. That is why I prefer Uncharted over Tomb Raider because Nathan Drake is just a way more fun character.  But at least this movie seem to have dual pistols, something the new games lacks. I will probably give it a chance at least, but then again it is a movie based on a game. Very few of those are good.

text: Did you ever notice how often decades old intellectual property is simply dusted off and represented to us as new?   I'm aware that giving an old concept a new lick of paint isn't exactly talentless, but creating a new concept is something that used to be done _as well as_ all the work that's required to give something a new paint job - the story, acting, design, production and editing, as well as creating a concept. Not just pulling an old idea out the draw of other people's work and saying 'new millenniumify it.'  What do we get when do try and create a concept, instead of relying on hand-me-downs? The sodding Emoji Movie.

author: G S

text: Frankly I don't get the hate on Alicia Vikander. She looks just wonderful and I'm excited to see her take this role. My only concern is how the story is going to play out. For those who played the 2013 reboot would know, the story wasn't a "Save the world" scenario. It started out as a group of explorers who washed up on an island, suddenly trying to get off said island, and then it got into the whole world resurrection of a evil Deity that would possibly destroy the world.  I wish it would go a bit that route, but it looks like they are telling the tale of Lara Croft trying to stop and save the world from impending doom, not the adventurers who washed up on an island. It would make for some greater suspense and horror angles I feel.   Lastly, is she already comfortable killing? Her first kill in the game made her break down, it was hard to do, and it was just to hunt and survive. Her first human kill was out of necessity to survive. I want to see this, but it looks like she was already comfortable beating up and killing bad guys.

text: Here's a tip to every director: if you're gonna make a movie, please don't base it on a video game! Other directors have went down that path, and nearly all of them failed miserably. Furthermore, if you absolutely have to make a game-based movie, at least understand the game first. The original Tomb Raider movies(with Angelina Jolie) were, in my opinion, fucking terrible. Angelina Jolie certainly had the Lara Croft look at the time, but it was ruined by the director's focus on the spectacle rather than substance. I could understand that since the original Tomb Raider games were heavily gameplay-oriented, but since this movie is based on the 2013 reboot(which was criticized for focusing too much on cinematics instead of actual exploration), it's going to be even more embarrassing if you fail to appeal to even that game.

text: Alright. I don't like it. Not saying the movie is shit, because this is just a trailer, the first one at that, HOWEVER, I do not like this trailer and it gives me the IMPRESSION that this movie will have bland dialogue, a story that was slopped together lazily, all possibly under the excuse that the source material would have accepted this kind of generic quality in its cutscenes. However, the reason videogames can get away with substandard dialogue and/or story is because they can make up for it with what their audience really craves: a fun game. This is a movie. You fail at dialogue and storytelling and you've already lost 50% of the money you could have made otherwise because that is exactly half of what movie audiences want from you. When it comes to videogames, dialogue and story (while they have grown in importance since) were more like 5% of what was needed back in Tomb Raider's heyday.

text: I don't think this is going to be the worst film ever made but holy **** every scene they showed was so dead. When they filmed this were all the actors told they should be as emotionless and uncommitted as humanly possible. Everyone and I mean everyone just seems to be going through the motions here. Of course it's only a trailer so who can say?! But I think we  can say lol. I really like the Tomb Raider reboots, and I think with the right filmakers, perhaps ones that actually give a *** about making something awesome out of this franchise, it could really be a fun movie. I don't know how to do Tomb Raider in a way that makes it more good than fun. It's just modern day Indiana Jones with boobs, at least I felt that way playing it as a kid. Even that is giving it too much credit somehow. But these recent games are a lot more complex. I don't think Lara is that interesting of a character, her story is told over and over with nothing really new brought to the table. Just rehash. text: Part of the appeal of Tomb Raider, the games, is that you play AS Laura and are an ACTIVE participant to what she does and what happens to her. A Tomb Raider movie, on the other hand, makes you a PASSIVE participant‚Äîpretty much a prisoner to the script, dialogue and choices.   This franchise, and any other where the original source is a video game are doomed to be crappy. I think you can make a successful game based on a movie, but not a successful movie based on a game.  A movie turned into a game EXPANDS the universe and possibilities and can provide dozens of hours of entertainment, with hundreds of choices of how the story unfolds.  A game turned into a movie CONSTRICTS the universe, diminishes possibilities and usually fails to provide the same level of entertainment because the (usually disconnected filmmakers) rush/condense/homogenize the story/characters/locations due to a usual 2-hour constraint.   Also, because of the simple fact that REAL people need to perform UNREAL acts in UNREAL situations, usually with the heavy use of unrealistic CG, the suspension of disbelief is harder to achieve.  In other words, movies based on video games are usually going to suck.

text: lol @ all the males getting pissed off because all they wanted from this trailer was a boner for Lara.  Get real, dickheads. Even Lara's in-game boobs have been scaled down for the reboot, so the fact that the actress' ones are smaller doesn't matter. And it wouldn't have mattered anyway, you don't cast a role for boobs (unless you're Michael Bay), you cast a role for authenticity. It isn't the best trailer I've ever seen, and video game films do tend to flop, but perhaps this will turn the tide. I'm gonna go see it, and more than anything I hope to find that Vikander was cast for her ability to play a convincing Lara Croft rather than just because she's a lookalike.  Besides, who needs boobs in a film when it's got Nick Frost? I'm still looking forward to this, and if you just came here for boobs, jog on, we don't want you.

text: Not gonna bet any money on this movie.... But i'm gonna see it. But gonna stugle to take the villain seriously sine i can't get the image of him with titts out of my head. But what i don't get is the casting... I don't mind the actress they've got in the role of Lara. Shes good. But they're taking so much from the new games. A lil taste of the classic games at the end there. But the actress playing Lara in the games is one hll of a hotie and clearly knows how to act. Why not just cast her? I allways wondered why they didn't just go that rout. She honestly looks more like a Lara to me then Alicia does.... But again, don't mind her. Shes great! But yeah. It's gonna be fun to see if this becomes another train wreck or if it'll be a passable movie. My expectations are very low. There's honestly just one video game movie i think stands any chance of being good. And that's the Metal Gear Solid movie. Mostly because the director seems to understand the source material he is working with. And his ready to break every rule in the book of film making to ensure the movie stays true to the games. But yet adding his own flavor to it all. And he seems to have Mr. Kojima's blessing so if any movie based on games is set up for success it's that. Won't be supprised if this one fails tough.

text: Ex-Machina required no acting skills, she was playing a robot. And she fit that role well, because that robot required the actress to possess innately bland and innocent facial features. The issue here is wholly different. The problem here isn't only that women aren't good fighters, which makes female action characters inherently unbelievable, but that 99% of the actresses out there look cringey just pretending to be fighting, running and jumping. Actresses need to have a very tailored skillset/talent/personality to pull it off, like Angelina Jolie (raw/aggressive facial features), Gal Gadot (tall/ex-military), Milla Jovovich (slavic facial features/soviet vibe) etc... The margin of error allowed in female action hero casting is exceedingly small.

text: The movie itself doesn't look bad. It seems to have a lot of action and stunts, which is great for an action movie. But it also feels like they're doing the same they did with Baywatch. Using the name of a classic TV show/video game, as an excuse for an action movie just to make more money. For me, they've totally ruined this by casting Alicia Vikander as Lara Croat. I'm not saying she isn't a talented actress. I'm just saying she's not a good Lara Croft, and I think the problem with her is that her features aren't very feminine. Lara Croft is supposed to be a femme fatale. Elegant and badass at the same time. Curvy and delicate, but intimidating. That's why people fell in love with Angelina Jolie. Long story short: Alicia Vikander looks like a little boy with long hair.

text: I definitely want to see more footage before I come to a conclusion. Still, the characters from the game seemed to fit the situation better. They should have definitely brought in Conrad Roth, as he was a great mentor and crucial to her transformation from a college student to a relentless adventurer. He also served to pass the torch from Laura's father to Laura.  If you think it's generic and not Tomb Raider, I DARE you to watch the trailer to the Tomb Raider game reboot (2013). I pre-ordered the reboot for the PS3, and finished it. I also bought and played through the graphically enhanced PS4 version. Because of that, I remember the storyline, characters, and scenes in the game.  If I have one criticism, is that the trailer feels like a shot for shot live action translation of the game. Go and watch the trailer and try to tell me that I am wrong. At least a third of it is 100% identical to what you see in the game.   I'm not sure how I feel about it yet, but I give them a lot of credit to sticking to the source material better than the MCU does.

text: Looks cringy. Alicia's okay, she's a good actress... but this is literally is ripping off the 2013 remake and butchering it. At least in the game Lara jumps off the sinking boat to reach the hand of a friend trying to save her. This movie she just grabs a huge ass bag and jumps into the middle of nowhere. How logical.  And don't get me started on the jump stunts. For a movie basing itself on the more realistic latter games, she jumps abnormally high. The old Lara used to do that. I prefer the old Lara, she was incredibly smart, tougher than most men and yet more feminine than most women and feared no obstacle. The new Lara is fairly feminine, physically weaker than most men she encounters, and isn't really that clever, she just gets lucky. I really don't get how the new Lara is a statement to female rights given the old Lara was more competent. So she had huge boobs. Big deal. So sexist, right? IMO mixing old Lara with the new is simply put, Stupid. It's a cash grab to silence both fans of the old and new. But we all know how things turn out when you try to please everyone. You end up pleasing no one.

text: The trailer looks bomb!   Few things from me though,  I hope we get to see more of the emotional side of Lara, so we can empathize with her character even more. That was a huge theme of the first game too, to humanize her. If she gets too bad ass (even though it's awesome) most of the audience wouldn't even flinch everytime she get's hurt or in a pickle situation. This is just a trailer so I'm not too worried.  I also don't like how they just narrates what lara supposed to do from what it seems like in this trailer. In the game she was never litteraly told by her father to "destroy the tomb blabla". She was given clues and a naturally curious person, and when she finds the problem she actually learns to solve it by herself. So it almost feels like they were watering down lara's father figure to me. But I hope the actual movie is not as straight forward as I thought it would be.  I know this is the movie and that was the game and those two were completely different media of story telling, but since they were tied I thought it would make sense to point out few things that's important to the story telling aspect to me. Still excited for the movie though! I thought it was never gonna happen

I'm not saying this movie's bad, it hasn't even come out yet but from the trailer alone, their mixed with what version they want, is it either the more marketable action heroin or the more vulnerable version of the character.   And from the people saying that, "the movie gives you the lara you wanted", yes it did gave us the lara we wanted... during the 90's and from the earlier movie versions of her, what we want now is a version of the character that reflects the growth of the industry and be the version that the reboot has done right.

And this gospel of the kingdom will be preached in the whole world as a testimony to  all nations, and then the end will come.  ‚ÄúSo when you see standing in the holy place ‚Äòthe  abomination that causes desolation,‚Äô spoken of through the prophet Daniel‚Äîlet the reader understand‚Äî  then let those who are in Judea flee to the mountains.  Let no one on the housetop go down to take anything out of the house. Let no one in the field go back to get their cloak. How dreadful it will be in  those days for pregnant women and nursing mothers! Pray that your flight will not take place in winter or on the Sabbath. 21 For then there will be great distress, unequaled from the beginning of the world until now‚Äîand never to be equaled again.  ‚ÄúIf those days had not been cut short, no one would survive, but for the sake of the elect those days will be shortened. At that time if anyone says to you, ‚ÄòLook, here is the Messiah!‚Äô or, ‚ÄòThere he is!‚Äô do not believe it.  For false messiahs and false prophets will appear and perform great signs and wonders to deceive, if possible, even the elect. See, I have told you ahead of time.  ‚ÄúSo if anyone tells you, ‚ÄòThere he is, out in the wilderness,‚Äô do not go out; or, ‚ÄòHere he is, in the inner rooms,‚Äô do not  believe it.For as lightning that comes from the east is visible even in the west, so will be the coming of the  Son of Man.  Wherever there is a carcass,  there the vultures will gather.  ‚ÄúImmediately after the distress of those days  ‚Äú‚Äòthe sun will be darkened, and the moon will not give its light; the stars will fall from the sky, and the heavenly bodies will be shaken.‚Äô  ‚ÄúThen will appear the sign of the Son of Man in  heaven. And then all the peoples of the earth will mourn  when they see the Son of Man coming on the clouds of  heaven, with power and great glory. And he will  send his angels with a loud trumpet call, and they will  gather his elect from the four winds, from one end of  the heavens to the other.  ‚ÄúNow learn this lesson from the fig tree: As soon as its twigs get tender and its leaves come out, you know that summer is near. Even so, when you see all these things, you know that it is near, right  at the door. Truly I tell you, this generation will  certainly not pass away until all these things have  happened. Heaven and earth will pass away,  but my words will never pass away.  The Day and Hour Unknown  ‚ÄúBut about that day or hour no one knows, not even the angels in heaven, nor the Son, but only the Father. As it was in the days of Noah, so it will be at the coming of the Son of Man. For in the days before the flood, people were eating and drinking, marrying and giving in marriage, up to the day Noah entered the ark; 39 and they knew nothing about what would happen until the flood came and took them all away. That is how it wil be  at the coming of the Son of Man. Two men will be in the field; one will be taken and the other left. Two women will be grinding with a hand mill;  one will be taken and the other left.  ‚ÄúTherefore keep watch, because you do not know on what day your Lord will come. But understand this: If the owner of the house had known at what time of night the thief was coming, he would have kept watch and would not have let his house be broken into.  So you also must be ready, because the Son of Man will come at an hour when you do not expect him.  ‚ÄúWho then is the faithful and wise servant,  whom the master has put in charge of the servants in his household to give them their food at  the proper time? It will be good for that servant whose master finds him doing so when he  returns. Truly I tell you, he will put him in charge of all his possessions.But suppose that servant is wicked and says to himself, ‚ÄòMy master is staying away a long time,‚Äô and he then begins to beat his  fellow servants and to eat and drink with drunkards. text: I will just put here comment of Gergely Gyurics becouse i think he  gets the main problem of this movie but its lost in answers of the other comment.  Actually it is nothing like the reboot game, that they promised. In the Square-Enix 2013 Tomb Raider Lara was not an action hero, nor a genious. She was a smart girl well versed in history and survival craft, but apart from that, she had a normal, real, actually relatable human psyche. She was afraid of going through wrecks over waterfalls, she had to talk to herself to calm down, she cried because of stress. Here, she is showed as the oldschool genious action hero she was in the Angelina Jolie movies, making hero poses with pistols and solving age old mysteries during her onboarding sessions.  It just... losts the whole birth of a hero feeling. Lara in the game was NOT ready. She had to constantly search and find new sources of inner strength, she had to face situations, where your only choices where terrible and dangerous, and had to grow up to it before your very eyes. You could see her in a situation where you know you WOULD have given up, because you could not do it, but she had no choice! Now she just goes in to kick ass while being sexy. And while that is fun to an extent - like for five minutes -, it does'nt make a good plot.  The story lost the... actually, what it lost was the story. From the trailer it looks just a sequence of poses, action and clich√© dialogues.

text: So... Let me get this straight. People in here aren't complaining about the quality of the trailer, or the story... But about her TITS??? What the hell is wrong with you? Here you have a trailer about a movie with decent cinematography, decent pre-production effects and an Oscar-Nominated actress, yet all you can point out is the bust size?  Newsflash: Women in real life do not have big busts like Mary Jane Watson/Sue Storm/Lara Croft. Maybe Hollywood was more interested in someone who could actually emote and give you a decent performance. Sure, the plot looks a bit thin, but the games were like that too. As long the main characters are great (one of them is being played by Walton Goggins, come on), the movie will be fine.  THIS is why we never get good video game adaptations. Because we complain about useless stuff and because we have the maturity of a 13 year old kid. No wonder studio executives do not take us seriously.

text: Am I the only one that sees this as a movie of the NEW Tomb Raider Lara Croft?  As in the 2013 Tomb Raider reboot game by Crystal Dynamics simply named "Tomb Raider".  To me this isn't the fully mature adult Lara, this is the archaeological student who was raised as a survivalist that begins taking after her father in examining such dangerous and powerful things that eventually leads her to become the legend.  Hell, the trailer even says "HER LEGEND BEGINS".  It also references an island in some dangerous zone(the Devil's Sea here whereas in the game it was called the Dragon's Triangle) where she gets shipwrecked and taken prisoner by the locals.  It seems to blend the first reboot and its sequel "Rise of the Tomb Raider" because the villain is an organization known as "Trinity" which is the primary antagonist of said game.   To me, Alicia Vikander pulls of that depiction of Lara wonderfully.  I'm excited for this movie, but apprehensive, as a lot of video game movies are garbage.  Here's hoping this one breaks the mold.

text: Wow, so much hate. The ghostbusters reboot? yeah, I could see why people judged it before movie was even out. This one? I don't see the problem with the trailer at all so why the hate? Half of the people complaining about "no boobs" which is a stupid thing to complain about. Also, as much as I like the character in movie to resemble the game one I think for movies you need talent over appearance. Nobody said shit when Peter Dinklage played bolivar trask in the xmen movie, mostly because he did a great job with the role. So why not give this movie the benefit of the doubt for now? While the trinity storyline is not the one I would have started with at least it looks like they are trying to be a bit more faithful to the game (well, the reboot) so that is always a step in the right direction. So for my part I will have cautious optimism. I know this is the internet and all but damn people, stop being so negative so soon.

text: Played the games (2013 Tomb Raider & 2015 Rise of the Tomb Raider) and enjoyed them a lot, but looking at this trailer does not give me high hopes for this movie. The whole trailer seemed like everyone spoke in excruciatingly bad one-liners, the special effects looked laughable, and the whole plot seems painfully predictable. Love the games and the character, but if the previous two movies have taught us anything, it's that Lara Croft should stay within the realms of video games. Hopefully I'm wrong and this movie will wind up being a hit. I mean, at least the casting is decent (Alicia Vikander & Walter Goggins are excellent casting choices). I suppose only time will tell.

text: This is one of those cases where it is too much of the game that I don't want to see it. It looks just like the game, but.. not. You'd think that'd be good, but it isn't. Looks boring. Should have just went with Uncharted, it was more than gameplay. It had good gameplay, voice actors, action, characters and chemistry. Nathan is a character I can like, and want to live. He's witty and likable, Lara, not so much. Tomb raider is just a game, and that will not translate well, especially with this robot. She looks like she's still playing one in EX machina. Lara Croft was mans character, that was her audience. The action, the body, and that was it. I can see they wanted more, and for her to be real by getting rid of the invincible and sexy babe aspect, but it still feels fake and not authentic. So after all that, why not just do Uncharted?

text: does not look like it will be good.  It seems like there will be little to no character development for Lara.  The whole point of the newer Tomb Raider games (which this looks to be based off of) is that Lara finds inner strength to continue on.  Sure, she knows how to shoot guns and stuff, but she doesn't go to the island expecting to use any, and her first time killing someone comes as quite a shock to her.  She shouldn't be billy bad ass at the beginning of the movie, but instead be an intelligent, normal young woman.  This is all speculation at this point, but the trailer, rather than encouraging me to see the movie, actually discourages me from watching it.

text: For all those complaining because it's using a cliche plot idea, please pick up a Tomb Raider game, primarily the 2013 game reboot. Secondly, wtf has been size got to do with how well someone can play Lara Croft? Game accuracy? You do realize in the early games her boobs were like arrow heads and to make them true to life you'd have to almost be able to cut glass with them. Or did you want her to look like she accidentally wandered on set from the Lego Movie? Lastly, there is nothing wrong with the casting. She looks the part, has the accent down and tbh it's unfair not to give her a chance before actually seeing how well she does in the movie. This could be awesome. We don't know. It at least looks like it's trying to follow the 2013 remake in some way (though I know it won't be completely the same), which is better than what they have done in the past. I love Jolie and she made a great Lara Croft but her Tomb Raider movies were terrible.

text: Well, as a big fan of the Tomb Raider series (both games and movies) I'd say this is mediocre. We all knew Angelina wouldn't play Lara again because she got older, and directors won't cast her again.  I mean, I grew up on her movies, and Tomb Raider was the one that left the most impact and influence on me. Now let me tell you why.   Lara Croft is a person that every female should look up to. She's independent, strong, fearless, smart, extremely attractive and capable. We've seen her fighting demi-gods, animals, humans, robots etc. We've seen her driving all sorts of vehicles. We've seen her solving every problem she got caught up in. Well, at least judging by all games I've played. I think Angelina was the perfect choice for Lara's character. She completely nailed her personality and she trained for months to get her physique. That's why audience LOVED Angelina, for completely taking down her character.   That's the Lara Croft we expect this actress to portray.   Sadly, I think that producers focused on the game that came out couple years ago, the only Tomb Raider game I disliked. Because it shows Lara before she became badass. She was trapped on that island, fighting for her dear life. It was cringe worthy for me to play the game, it's not the Lara I was used to. So making a movie based on that plot is just going to be bad. Everyone is used to Lara the way she was back when Angelina shot the two movies.   I'll watch this nonetheless, but I'm ready to be disappointed. Also the main actress looks very lifeless, where are her badass facial expressions? Like, who am I watching? Lara Croft or some random scared chick? üòß

text: Okay time to make an actual contribution here... When I saw a picture of the new tomb raider movie with Lara in her tank top and pick axe my entitial thoughts were oh cool maybe this will be good because they seem to understand that the rebooted game did super well and that they should have the same focus. However after seeing more from the trailer it looks like they don't understand why the game did so well because it has none of the meat and just the bare bones. They reduce all of the key characters from the game like Lara's mentor to one character who will likely be a love interest. Boo. The games did so well because of the story not purely because of the action which they seemed to fall back on yet again. Next time you make another game movie or reboot of something popular try doing some damn research into what made it so popular. Find some fans and ask them instead of presuming you understand when you don't. At best chances are that this will be just an okay movie but a giant missed opportunity because of people who can't relate to the fan base.

text: You have to admit that the most recent two reboot games for the Tomb Raider series have been an incredible breath of fresh air. Especially in "Rise of the Tomb Raider", when i completed it i felt a great connection with the story line and the characters, the tasks were just hard enough to merit a feeling of accomplishment. That being said, video game reboots flounder the most because the whole point of a video game is self immersion and choice making... This looks entertaining but it looks like we are just watching a play through of the most recent two games. The story has so much potential and the voice acting in the game was surprisingly well done. I would recommend anyone with 10 dollars and a decent computer to play Rise of the Tomb Raider now while its less than 10 dollars on steam, just to get a little more immersed in the story line.

Alicia Vikander is Lara Croft. #TombRaider Review :   http://reviewmoviemagz.blogspot.com/2017/09/tomb-raider-warner-bros-pictures-metro.html --  Lara Croft, the fiercely independent daughter of a missing adventurer, must push herself beyond her limits when she finds herself on the island where her father disappeared.   From Warner Bros. Pictures and Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer Pictures, Tomb Raider is the story that will set a young and resolute Lara Croft on a path toward becoming a global hero.  The film stars Oscar winner Alicia Vikander (Ex Machina, The Danish Girl) in the lead role, under the direction of Roar Uthaug (The Wave), with Oscar-winner Graham King (The Departed) producing under his GK Films banner.  The film¬πs production begins on the heels of the 20th anniversary of the wildly popular videogame franchise from Square Enix, Crystal Dynamics and Eidos Montreal.  Tomb Raider also stars Dominic West (Money Monster, 300), Walton Goggins (The Hateful Eight, Django Unchained) and Daniel Wu (AMC¬πs Into the Badlands). --    Follow #TombRaiderMovie On Social Media :  https://twitter.com/tombraidermovie http://www.tombraidermovie.com/ https://www.facebook.com/TombRaiderMovie https://www.instagram.com/tombraidermovie/

text: This looks like its based heavily on the 2013 tomb raider (game). And if that is true (im 97% sure of this), then they are trying to make Lara Croft into what she is in her later adventures: experienced. And in the game they made sure to make her afraid, uncertain and hurt (a lot) to make her a dynamic character, and to make her more relatable. And i believe they did a great job in that factor in the game. But here they are trying to make it out that shes done all this before and all like she knows what to do. And thats an awful idea. Stop trying to make it out that all main characters have to be strong from the getgo to make them good. Id rather watch an actor hide in fear at the start and then become a confident, badass who could conquer the world later on. Do research Hollywood, its called character development. text: 'Tempus fugit' time flies. When you realise how quick life passes you by. The original film in 2001, now with a remake in 2018. When you wake up and think what have you done with your life since the original. When you find out Eidos Interactive is no more and never heard of Square Enix... Square What?  When you remember skipping College to play Tomb Raider on the PS1 then returning the next day to find everyone hooked up to the LAN playing Quake 1... When you think you prefer the original with Angelina Jolie, I mean really can you really make it any better than the first, but when you have an interest in the new film... When you watch the trailer and then hope for so much more then think again of the original.... When you have watched the first one so many times you know all the words.... When you realise you won't remember any of the words of the new version and probably not watch it hundreds of times but just a few.... When you hope Angelina will do a Sean Connery and come back as Lara in 'Tomb Raider: Never Say Never'....When Dr Who becomes a lady and hear rumours about the next James Bond being a female and wonder where it will stop. Will the next Lara be a man? Hang on that is Indiana Jones. When you wonder if Chris Barrie from Red Dwarf will make a special guest appearance as the Butler in slippers and shotgun... When you really enjoyed the amazing cars bikes and guns of the original watch the trailer for the new one and find out Lara is now riding a bicycle and firing arrows...  When you work out that there is so much CGI in films these days is any of it real... When you know you will watch it anyway... When you appreciate a new Tomb Raider film but can't help but wonder how Time Flies...

text: I mean... I feel like I want to see it because I like Tomb Raider... but I'm seeing a lot of that whole "superhero posture" thing going on.  *superhero posture* "I'll take two."  Um... okay? Thanks for coming by the shop. I'll phone you in about a week while your background check goes through... crazy lady. Lol.  I'm sorry but this just gets way too cringy for me. The game was wonderful because it showed how human Lara Croft is. How she perseveres DESPITE the fact that she gets impaled by a rusty spike, or gets shot by bloodthirsty men who want to skin her.  She takes the scars and gets dished some serious punishment, but always licks her wounds, and by the overwhelming will to survive, manages to succeed in spite of those injuries.  If they turn her into some sort of crazy superhero, they've broken the new Lara into a cheap action motif. It's boring. There's no humanity to it.  Sorry, but I'm going to have to pass on this movie. Hollywood dropped the ball yet again.  Leave the whole superhero thing to Marvel or DC. Make something novel. Make something human.

text: Well technically you could almost count Jumanji as a success. As it was based within a game story format. That probably is going to be as close as we're ever going to get to any kind of true success story here.   As far as Tomb Raider goes it sounds like it's a hit and miss.  For starters Alicia as good as she is was completely miscast here.   Not nearly as painful as her husband in Assassin's Creed. But bad enough to pretty much guarantee another 10 years in the crypt vault lol.   I was really hoping it was going to be different this time but it seems that directors just can't help themselves.   Always thinking they can do a better job than what the original source material had given us.   Seriously I was expecting something with a little bit more effort put forth here. Instead of just cheery picking scenes.   Then copy and pasting a script on top of it as that's just lazy writing. Hollywood needs to do us a favor and just stop embarrassing themselves. R.I.P. Tomb Raider

text: Now I can't deny that we all had expectations for this movie. But looking at it rationally this movie was executed really poorly, lacked proper explanations and missed the entire point of tomb rider's universe. Actors did quite a good job, and the cinematics were pretty too, but this movie just lacked the tomb raider spirit. Counting the fact that they relied on 2013 tomb raider game's plot they should've just stuck to it rather than turning himiko into ebola spreading mummy or making lara's and her father's reunion the only magical moment in the entire movie. It's like creators knew nothing of the franchise. They completely wasted all the potential that tomb raider world could have offered, and created another soulless hollywood "action" movie. Go play the game. This movie ain't worth your money.

Tan solo nombrare 3 aspectos fundamentales que estan fuera de todo contexto con la verdadera historia: 1 lara no  es y nunca ha sido una empleada,  repartidora ni nada por el estilo, mucho menos se  comporta asi menos teniendo 21 a√±os, ese comportamiento ni siquiera se da a los 15, pero que les pasa a los productores y/o escritores?  2 Lara nunca en su vida encuentra a su padre vivo, menos lo encuentra como un vil andrajoso y casi loco, tan solo lo ve en visiones y con ayuda de artefactos extra√±os. 3 La princesa himiko nunca habia estado enferma ni es portadora de ninguna enfermedad, pero que le pasa a esta gente que escribe??  Estamos viendo otra repeticion en la cual encuentran otro tipo de caja de pandora, la cual tambien tiene una plaga o enfermedad que afecta a la humanidad tipo tomb raider la cuna de la vida??? Himiko era la reina del sol, controlaba sol y la lluvia, por eso no se podia ir a esa isla tan facil ni salir. Que desepcion de historia, en cuanto a lo demas pues esta bien, efectos y eso pues comun, pero historia, cero, para nada, que lastima que da√±en las cosas asi......

text: ...It's based on the 2013 game. Credit where it's due: The games are very well made.  But it's not Tomb Raider, on principle.  Tomb Raider was like the Legend of Zelda with guns, and a badass female lead;   ALSO FIGHTING A T-REX.  Tomb Raider 2013 would be like making Pokemon into a super edgy, hyper violent monster summoning anime where the Poke-balls are magical artifacts and the Pokemon kill each other.  Or like turning Grand Theft Auto into a "Street Gangsta works undercover for the police to overthrow an illegal network of car-thieves and chop-shops".  Or like if they remade Devil May Cry's Dante into a hard-boiled detective who has to stop a secret demon invasion when he learns that his father, who taught him the trade of being a Private Investigator, was actually a demon spy who betrayed the armies of Hell and discovers he has super powers.  That'd be like if Resident Evil swapped out Umbrella and the B.O.W.s for a Necromancer Cult and supernatural zombies and demons.  The 2013 remake completely took the game and turned it upside down and removed everything that made Tomb Raider an individual compared to other games.

text: I had not watched this before.  Decided to do it today.  I stopped watching well before halfway.  She just pawned something her father gave her, so she can fund her trip.  All suspension of belief is gone at this point.  I can already see it...they sat around a table, and said, "No, we can't have her sign the papers and suddenly be wealthy, to fund her trip, which may be the sane choice that literally what every last real human would do...no, let's have her pawn something her father gave her...but to make it more interesting, let's make it seem like she is now going to be operating on a shoestring budget.  That way her accomplishments aren't because of her daddy's money...because daddy's are evil and bad and stuff...and so is their money...unless we want new shoes, or a new car."   Movies such now.  Technology is such that all movies should pretty dang good, but they can't resist the feminist, SJW bs, and so they literally ruin every movie they make now.

text: Despite the hype this is fairy ok movie. The problem here is bad casting.  The female lead characters should be a strong feminist. AV did her best in this movie. she is a very good method actress. Best suited for innocent,fragile characters such as Light between Oceans, Royal affair. She doesn't has the strong feminist look or frame. Imagine Iron Man played by someone other than Robert J or Wolverine played by some one other than Huge J or Thanos. Casting does miracles. If found the right match it shines. Unfortunately they made a bad casting. And movie is also has lot of plot holes. Though Anjelina is bad actress she is best suited for feminism. If this is a movie a girl lost a father at young age and again find him and with some adventure this could have been acceptable. For a Tomb Raider movie this plot is horrible. Being a countess the female lead can't speak multi languages and does learn combat skills in a cheap dojo doesn't add up with a girl with such a rich lineage. And who the hell wan't to remove a mummy from a tomb. Because it is the most valuable part of the treasure. Usually tomb robbers take the tomb. And father lived there for years with out seen by any one with out food is also incredible.
